# **üìå Ultimate Guide: Set Up a Static IP, Dynamic DNS (No-IP), and SSH Remote Access on Windows 11 Using PowerShell ‚Äì Connect From Anywhere in the World!**

This guide will walk you through setting up a **Static IP, Dynamic DNS (DDNS) with No-IP, and OpenSSH on Windows 11** to allow remote SSH access from anywhere in the world. üöÄ  
You will learn how to:
‚úÖ **Set a Static IP for Your Windows PC**  
‚úÖ **Use No-IP to Assign a Domain Name to Your Changing Public IP**  
‚úÖ **Configure Your Router to Allow SSH Traffic (Port Forwarding)**  
‚úÖ **Enable and Secure OpenSSH on Windows 11**  
‚úÖ **Fix SSH Authentication Errors (Public Key or Password Issues)**  
‚úÖ **Test SSH Access from a Different Network to Ensure It Works**  

---

## **Step 1: Create a Free No-IP DDNS**
Since most ISPs assign **dynamic (changing) IPs**, you need No-IP to always access your computer using a **fixed domain name** instead of checking your IP manually.

1Ô∏è‚É£ **Go to** [No-IP](https://www.noip.com/) and **sign up**.  
2Ô∏è‚É£ **Verify your email** and **log in**.  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Navigate to **"Dynamic DNS"** and click **"Create Hostname"**.  
4Ô∏è‚É£ Enter a hostname (e.g., `michaelovsky.ddns.net`).  
5Ô∏è‚É£ Select **"DNS Host (A)"** and click **"Create Hostname"**.  

---

## **Step 2: Install the No-IP Dynamic Update Client (DUC) on Windows 11**
This ensures your No-IP hostname (`michaelovsky.ddns.net`) **always points to your public IP, even if it changes**.

1Ô∏è‚É£ **Download the No-IP DUC Client**: [Download Here](https://www.noip.com/download).  
2Ô∏è‚É£ Install and **log in** with your No-IP credentials.  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Select your hostname (`michaelovsky.ddns.net`) and **click "Save"**.  
4Ô∏è‚É£ **Minimize the client** so it runs in the background.  
   - **To make No-IP update automatically on startup**, go to **Settings ‚Üí Startup** and enable **"Run on Startup"**.

---

## **Step 3: Assign a Static Local IP to Your Windows 11 PC**
To ensure **port forwarding works correctly**, your PC **must always have the same internal IP**.

### **‚û°Ô∏è Using PowerShell**
1Ô∏è‚É£ Open **PowerShell as Administrator**.  
2Ô∏è‚É£ Check your **current network settings**:
   ```powershell
   Get-NetIPConfiguration
   ```
   - **Note your** `InterfaceIndex` (e.g., `4`).
   - **Note your** `Gateway (Router IP)` (e.g., `192.168.1.1`).

3Ô∏è‚É£ Assign a **static IP address** to your PC:
   ```powershell
   New-NetIPAddress -InterfaceIndex 4 -IPAddress 192.168.1.100 -PrefixLength 24 -DefaultGateway 192.168.1.1
   ```
4Ô∏è‚É£ Set **Google DNS for reliability**:
   ```powershell
   Set-DnsClientServerAddress -InterfaceIndex 4 -ServerAddresses ("8.8.8.8","8.8.4.4")
   ```
5Ô∏è‚É£ Verify settings:
   ```powershell
   ipconfig /all
   ```
   - **Ensure your IPv4 Address is `192.168.1.100`**.
   - **Ensure your DNS is `8.8.8.8, 8.8.4.4`**.

---

## **Step 4: Configure Port Forwarding on Your Router**
Your router **blocks SSH by default**. You must **forward port 22** to your PC.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Log into your **router‚Äôs web interface** (`192.168.1.1` in a browser).  
2Ô∏è‚É£ Find **"Port Forwarding"** (under **Advanced Settings/NAT**).  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Add a new rule:  
   - **Service Name:** SSH  
   - **Protocol:** TCP  
   - **External Port:** `22`  
   - **Internal IP Address:** `192.168.1.100`  
   - **Internal Port:** `22`  
4Ô∏è‚É£ **Save & Apply** changes.  

---

## **Step 5: Enable and Configure OpenSSH on Windows 11**
Windows 11 **includes an SSH server**, but you must enable it.

### **‚û°Ô∏è Install and Start SSH on Windows 11**
1Ô∏è‚É£ Open **PowerShell as Administrator** and install OpenSSH Server:
   ```powershell
   Add-WindowsCapability -Online -Name OpenSSH.Server*
   ```
2Ô∏è‚É£ **Start the SSH service**:
   ```powershell
   Start-Service sshd
   ```
3Ô∏è‚É£ **Set SSH to start automatically**:
   ```powershell
   Set-Service -Name sshd -StartupType Automatic
   ```

---

## **Step 6: Allow SSH Through Windows Firewall**
Your **Windows firewall might block SSH**, so allow it manually.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Open **PowerShell as Administrator** and run:
   ```powershell
   New-NetFirewallRule -Name sshd -DisplayName 'OpenSSH Server' -Enabled True -Direction Inbound -Protocol TCP -Action Allow -LocalPort 22
   ```

---

## **Step 7: Test SSH Access**
### **‚û°Ô∏è Try SSH from Another Device**
On another PC or phone, try:
```powershell
ssh micha@michaelovsky.ddns.net
```
If you get:
```
Permission denied (publickey,password).
```
Follow **Step 8** to fix it.

---

## **Step 8: Fix SSH Authentication Errors**
### **‚úÖ Fix 1: Enable Password Authentication (Easiest)**
1Ô∏è‚É£ Open **PowerShell as Administrator** and edit SSH config:
   ```powershell
   notepad C:\ProgramData\ssh\sshd_config
   ```
2Ô∏è‚É£ Find:
   ```
   PasswordAuthentication no
   ```
   Change it to:
   ```
   PasswordAuthentication yes
   ```
3Ô∏è‚É£ Restart SSH:
   ```powershell
   Restart-Service sshd
   ```
4Ô∏è‚É£ Now SSH should prompt for your **Windows password**.

---

## **Step 9: Final Test ‚Äì Check SSH from a Different Network**
‚úÖ **To ensure everything works, test SSH from a network that is NOT your home network.**  

### **‚û°Ô∏è Test SSH from a Mobile Hotspot or Another Network**
1Ô∏è‚É£ **Turn off Wi-Fi** on your **laptop or another device**.  
2Ô∏è‚É£ **Use a mobile hotspot** or go to a **friend‚Äôs house or caf√©**.  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Open **PowerShell** and type:
   ```powershell
   ssh micha@michaelovsky.ddns.net
   ```
4Ô∏è‚É£ **If it works**, congratulations! üéâ You can now SSH into your Windows 11 machine from anywhere in the world! üöÄ  
5Ô∏è‚É£ **If it fails**, check:
   - **No-IP Client (DUC) is running** and updating your IP.
   - **Router Port Forwarding is set correctly**.
   - **Firewall rules allow SSH**.
   - **Your ISP is not blocking port 22** (if so, try port `2222` instead).

---

## **üéØ Conclusion**
You **now have full SSH access** to your Windows 11 PC from **anywhere in the world** using No-IP and PowerShell! üöÄ

